  {
    id: "how-git-works",
    category: "Technology",
    title: "Version Control & How Git Works",
    tagline: "Beneath the everyday commands lies an elegant object store — a tamper-evident graph of every state your work has ever been in.",
    color: "#b0623a",
    glyph: "⎇",
    levels: [
      {
        depth: 1,
        title: "A First Glimpse",
        body: `<p>You know the small dread. You have a document that finally works — the report, the chapter, the program that compiles — and now you want to change it, but changing it might break it. So you make a copy. You name it <code>final</code>. Then you change your mind, and there is <code>final_v2</code>, and then <code>final_v2_REALLY_final</code>, and a week later you are staring at a folder full of near-identical files, unsure which one is the good one.</p><p>Now imagine the same problem with five people editing at once, emailing versions back and forth, each quietly overwriting the others' work. This is the chaos that version control was invented to end.</p><p>Git is the tool that, for most of the world's software, ended it. Think of it as a time machine bolted to your project: at any moment you can step back to exactly how things were last Tuesday, or open a parallel universe where you try a wild idea without endangering the version that works, and then either keep that universe or discard it as if it never happened. Nothing good is ever truly lost.</p><p>And here is the surprise. Git has a reputation for cryptic, intimidating commands. Yet beneath them sits one of the most elegant data structures in all of everyday software — a quiet little machine for remembering.</p>`,
        pullQuote: "A time machine bolted to your project: nothing good is ever truly lost."
      },
      {
        depth: 2,
        title: "Snapshots, Not Differences",
        body: `<p>Most people assume that version control stores <em>changes</em> — that each save records the lines you added and deleted, stacked in a neat chronological pile. It is a reasonable guess, and it is how some older systems worked. Git does something stranger and, in the end, simpler. Git stores <strong>snapshots</strong>. Every time you commit, it conceptually photographs the entire state of your project — every file, every folder — and files that photograph away.</p><p>This sounds wasteful until you learn the second idea, the one that makes the whole thing sing: Git is <strong>content-addressed</strong>. Every object Git stores is named not by you, and not by where it sits, but by a hash of its own contents — a short fingerprint computed from the bytes inside it. Change a single character and the fingerprint changes completely. Keep the bytes identical and the fingerprint is identical, so Git stores that content exactly once, no matter how many snapshots contain it.</p><p>From this fall three kinds of object. A <strong>blob</strong> is the contents of a file. A <strong>tree</strong> is a directory: a list of names paired with the hashes of the blobs and trees inside it. A <strong>commit</strong> is a snapshot in time — it points to one tree (the whole project, that instant) plus a note of who made it, when, and why, and crucially a pointer to its <em>parent</em>, the commit that came before.</p><p>String those parent-pointers together and you get the shape that defines Git: a <strong>directed acyclic graph</strong>, a DAG, where history flows from past to present and can fork and rejoin but never loop back on itself. And branches and tags — the things that sound so weighty in tutorials — are revealed to be almost nothing at all: just movable labels, sticky notes pointing at one commit in the graph.</p>`,
        pullQuote: "Every object is named by a fingerprint of its own contents."
      },
      {
        depth: 3,
        title: "The Object Model, in Detail",
        body: `<p>Let us open the hood. Inside every Git repository is a hidden folder, <code>.git</code>, and inside it an object database. Everything Git knows about your project's history lives there as those three object types, each stored under the key that <em>is</em> its content's hash.</p><p>A <strong>blob</strong> holds raw file contents and nothing else — no filename, no permissions, no timestamp, just bytes. This is why renaming a file moves no data: the blob is unchanged, so its hash is unchanged, and only the directory listing that mentions it is rewritten.</p><p>A <strong>tree</strong> is that directory listing. Each entry records a mode (file or subdirectory, executable or not), a name, and the hash of the blob or tree it refers to. A project's top-level tree points to subtrees, which point to further subtrees and blobs — a nested structure mirroring your folders exactly.</p><p>A <strong>commit</strong> ties it together. It stores the hash of one tree (the complete snapshot), the hash of its parent commit or commits, the author and committer with timestamps, and your message. Originally Git computed all these hashes with <strong>SHA-1</strong>, producing the familiar 40-character hexadecimal IDs like <code>e83c5163</code>. Because a hash is derived purely from contents, the store is self-verifying: re-hash any object and you can prove it has not been altered.</p><p>Between your files and the next commit sits the <strong>staging area</strong>, also called the <em>index</em> — a draft of the snapshot you are about to take. When you <code>git add</code> a file, you are not saving it forever; you are placing it on the staging table, composing your proposed next photograph. <code>git commit</code> then freezes that proposal into a permanent commit object.</p><p>With that picture, the everyday verbs lose their mystery. To <strong>commit</strong> is to write a new commit object pointing at the current parent and a fresh tree. To create a <strong>branch</strong> is to write a new movable label pointing at a commit — a single line in a file, nothing more. To <strong>merge</strong> two branches is to make a new commit with <em>two</em> parents, knitting two lines of history into one. To <strong>rebase</strong> is to lift a sequence of commits off one base and replant them atop another, rewriting them as you go. Every operation, underneath, is a small surgery on the graph.</p>`
      },
      {
        depth: 4,
        title: "Merkle Trees and the Architecture of Trust",
        body: `<p>Content-addressing is not merely a clever filing scheme. It is the doorway to a deeper structure, and understanding that structure explains why Git can be trusted to guard years of work.</p><p>Because a tree object contains the <em>hashes</em> of its children, and a commit contains the hash of its tree and of its parent, the hashes are chained all the way down. This arrangement has a name: a <strong>Merkle tree</strong>, after Ralph Merkle, who patented the idea in 1979 — more precisely a <strong>Merkle DAG</strong>, since history branches and rejoins. The defining property is transitivity. A node's hash depends on its contents, which include the hashes of its children, which depend on <em>their</em> children, and so on to the leaves. So the hash at the top covers everything beneath it.</p><p>Follow the consequence. A commit's hash is computed from its tree and its parent's hash. Its parent's hash was computed from <em>that</em> commit's tree and <em>its</em> parent — and so on back to the very first commit. Therefore a single commit ID is a <strong>cryptographic fingerprint of its entire ancestry</strong>: every file in every snapshot that ever led to this moment. Alter one byte in one file in one ancient commit, and that commit's hash changes, which changes its child's hash, which cascades all the way to the present. Tampering cannot hide; it announces itself by breaking the chain. The store is, in the proper sense, <em>tamper-evident</em>.</p><p>This is the same idea that secures very different systems. A blockchain such as Bitcoin is a Merkle-chained ledger whose every block fingerprints its predecessor. The peer-to-peer file system <strong>IPFS</strong> addresses all content by hash in a Merkle DAG, so that a name guarantees its data. Git arrived at the structure first, in 2005, for the humbler purpose of remembering source code.</p><p>Two further principles complete the design. The object store is <strong>append-only and immutable</strong>: objects are written once and never modified in place. What looks like editing history — amending a commit, rebasing — does not alter old objects; it creates <em>new</em> ones with new hashes and merely points the labels elsewhere, leaving the originals untouched until garbage collection eventually reclaims the unreferenced ones. And Git is <strong>distributed by design</strong>. When you clone a repository you receive not a thin checkout but the entire object database — every commit, every version, the whole Merkle DAG. There is no privileged central copy in the model itself; GitHub is a convention, not a requirement. Every clone is a full, self-sufficient repository, which is precisely why work survives outages, lost laptops, and abandoned servers.</p>`
      },
      {
        depth: 5,
        title: "Merges, Packfiles, and Reading Raw Objects",
        body: `<p>Now the machinery in earnest. When you merge two branches that have genuinely diverged, Git performs a <strong>three-way merge</strong>. The three inputs are the two branch tips and their <strong>merge base</strong> — the most recent commit that is an ancestor of both, the lowest common ancestor in the DAG. Git compares each tip against that base: a hunk changed on only one side is taken automatically; a hunk changed on both sides, differently, is a <strong>conflict</strong>, which Git marks with <code>&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;</code>, <code>=======</code>, <code>&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;</code> markers and asks you to resolve. The result becomes a merge commit with two parents.</p><p>If one branch is simply ahead of the other — the base <em>is</em> the older tip — there is nothing to reconcile, and Git performs a <strong>fast-forward</strong>: it slides the label forward with no new commit at all. A <strong>rebase</strong>, by contrast, takes your commits, computes the patch each one introduced, and <em>replays</em> them one by one onto a new base. Because each replayed commit now has a different parent (and possibly different content), it is a brand-new object with a brand-new hash. This is the heart of the warning never to rebase shared history: you are not moving commits, you are manufacturing impostors and orphaning the originals.</p><p>For storage, Git would be profligate if it kept every snapshot whole. So it periodically writes <strong>packfiles</strong>, in which similar objects are stored as <em>deltas</em> — one object recorded in full, others as compact instructions for transforming it — and the whole pack is zlib-compressed. Delta compression is chosen heuristically across the repository, not tied to commit order, which is why a large history can collapse to a remarkably small <code>.git</code> directory.</p><p>Safety lives in the <strong>reflog</strong>. Every time a label like <code>HEAD</code> or a branch moves, Git records the previous position in a local log. So even after a reckless <code>reset --hard</code> or a botched rebase, the supposedly lost commits are still in the object store, and <code>git reflog</code> will show you the hash to recover them. <strong>HEAD</strong> itself is just a pointer to your current branch; check out a raw commit instead of a branch and you enter <strong>detached HEAD</strong> — working atop a commit no label is tracking, where new commits risk being garbage-collected unless you name them.</p><p>You can see all of this directly. Git ships a "plumbing" command, <code>git cat-file</code>, that reads the raw store:</p><pre>$ git cat-file -t e83c5163      # what type is this object?
commit
$ git cat-file -p e83c5163      # print its contents
tree 7c4e8b...
parent 3a9f12...
author Ada Lovelace &lt;ada@example.com&gt; 1748736000 +0000
committer Ada Lovelace &lt;ada@example.com&gt; 1748736000 +0000

Fix the off-by-one in the carriage loop</pre><p>Print the tree it names and you get a directory listing of names and hashes; print one of those blob hashes and you get a file's exact contents. You can even compute an object's name yourself: Git hashes the bytes <code>"blob " + length + "\\0" + contents</code>. There is no hidden magic — only hashes, all the way down.</p>`
      },
      {
        depth: 6,
        title: "Collisions, Monorepos, and the Frontier of Versioning",
        body: `<p>Content-addressing rests on one assumption: that two different things never share a hash. For SHA-1 that assumption frayed. Cryptographers had warned for years that SHA-1 was weakening, and in February 2017 a team at Google and CWI Amsterdam announced <strong>SHAttered</strong> — the first practical SHA-1 collision, two distinct PDF files with the same digest, produced with enormous but feasible computation. For a content-addressed store this is existential: if an attacker can craft two objects with the same name, the guarantee that a hash uniquely identifies its contents collapses, and tamper-evidence with it. Git's exposure was limited (it added a collision-detecting variant of SHA-1, and its object framing differs from a raw PDF), but the writing was on the wall. The project has since defined a parallel object format using <strong>SHA-256</strong>, with interoperability between the two hash worlds an ongoing engineering effort led by maintainer <strong>Junio Hamano</strong> and contributors such as Brian Carlson. The episode is a clean lesson in what <em>collision resistance</em> actually buys an integrity system, and how a foundational primitive can age out from under a design.</p><p>The other great pressure is <strong>scale</strong>. Git was built for the Linux kernel — large, but text. Companies like Microsoft, Google, and Meta run <strong>monorepos</strong> with millions of files and decades of history, where a naive clone would download tens of gigabytes nobody needs. The answers reshape Git's assumption that every clone is the whole repository. <strong>Shallow clones</strong> fetch only recent history; <strong>partial clones</strong> defer downloading blobs until they are actually read; <strong>sparse checkout</strong> populates only the directories you work in. Microsoft built <strong>VFS for Git</strong> (originally GVFS), virtualizing the working tree so files materialize on access, and later <strong>Scalar</strong>, much of which has been folded back into mainline Git. The model bends toward "a full repository in principle, lazily realized in practice."</p><p>Git did not end the conversation about how version control <em>should</em> work. <strong>Mercurial</strong>, born the same month as Git in 2005, made nearly the same choices with a gentler interface. <strong>Fossil</strong>, written by SQLite's D. Richard Hipp, bundles a wiki and bug tracker into the repository itself. Most intriguing is <strong>Pijul</strong>, which abandons the snapshot-and-replay model for a rigorous <em>theory of patches</em> grounded in category theory, aiming to make merges associative and commutative — so that the order in which changes arrive cannot change the result, a property Git's three-way merge does not guarantee. Darcs pioneered this patch-theoretic path before it; Pijul tries to make it fast.</p><p>Open questions remain genuinely open. Merge algorithms still operate on lines of text and stumble on moved code, refactors, and structured data; <em>syntactic</em> and <em>semantic</em> merge tools are an active research area. Real conflict-free collaboration on shared documents is handled today by CRDTs in editors, not by Git. And version control for <strong>non-text artifacts</strong> — images, datasets, 3D models, machine-learning model weights — remains awkward, served by bolt-ons like Git LFS and separate systems like DVC rather than by the object store itself. <strong>Linus Torvalds</strong> wrote the first Git in ten days in April 2005, after the kernel community lost access to the proprietary tool BitKeeper, then handed the project to Hamano, who has shepherded it ever since. Two decades on, the little machine for remembering is nearly universal — and still, quietly, unfinished.</p>`,
        pullQuote: "Only hashes, all the way down — until the day a hash is no longer unique."
      }
    ]
  }
